# Get ready to add another server

You learned how to use Chef to bring up a web server and serve a home page that displays some basic info about the server. You configured the server by running the commands directly on it, which is a great way to experiment with Chef.

But now you're ready to add a second server. You _could_ do this manually by installing the Chef tools, copying over your cookbooks, and running the Chef commands &ndash; all on the second server. But is there a better way?

_Chef server_ is a great place to serve as a central hub for your cookbooks. In this lesson you'll set up a Chef server and upload your cookbook to it. In the process, you'll also learn about <codeinline>knife</codeinline>, the tool that enables you to communicate with the Chef server.

## <i class="fa fa-question-circle blueiconcolor" style="margin-right:3px;"></i> All set up?

If you haven't completed the [previous tutorial](/rhel/make-your-recipe-more-manageable/), we recommend that you do.

You'll need a computer ready to install the Chef tools on. If you're not ready to install it on your workstation, you can continue to use our [CentOS training lab](/rhel/get-a-virtual-machine/), which has the tools already installed.

