## 1. Sign up for Hosted Enterprise Chef

The easiest way to set up a Chef server is to let us host it for you on Hosted Enterprise Chef. To get set up, just fill out the form on our sign up page.

<a class='button radius' href='<%= hec_sign_up_url %>' target='_blank'>Sign up for a free trial of Hosted Enterprise Chef&nbsp;&nbsp;<i class='fa fa-external-link'></i></a>

Now you need to download some files that enable you to communicate with the Chef server.

## 2. Install the Starter Kit

The Starter Kit provides certificates and other files that enable you to securely communicate with the Chef server. Follow these steps from your workstation.

  1. Navigate to <%= link_to "#{hec_manage_url}", "#{hec_manage_url}", :target => "_blank" %> and sign in.
  1. From the **Administration** tab, choose the organization that you created when you signed up for Hosted Enterprise Chef.
  1. From the **Actions** column, select **Starter Kit**.
  1. Click the **Download Starter Kit** button.
  1. Click **Proceed**. Save the file <filepath>chef-starter.zip</filepath> to your computer.
  1. Extract <filepath>chef-starter.zip</filepath> to your working directory, <filepath>~/chef-repo</filepath>.

## 3. Upload your cookbook to the Chef server

Now let's upload our web server cookbook to the Chef server. From anywhere under your <filepath>chef-repo</filepath> directory, run this command.

```bash
# ~/chef-repo
$ knife cookbook upload webserver
```

